TY  - JOUR
T1  - Seasonal Fluctuations and the Life Cycle-Permanent Income Model of Consumption
AU  - Miron, Jeffrey A.
Y1  - 1986/12/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261432
DO  - 10.1086/261432
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1258
EP  - 1279
VL  - 94
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines a new possible explanation for the recent rejections of the life cycle-permanent income model of consumption: the treatment of seasonal fluctuations. The paper shows that when the seasonal fluctuations in consumption purchases are included in an analysis of the life cycle-permanent income model, there is no evidence in the aggregate data against the model. The estimates of the parameters of agents' utility functions obtained with seasonally unadjusted data are plausible, and the unadjusted data do not reject the overidentifying restrictions on the model.
AB  - This paper examines a new possible explanation for the recent rejections of the life cycle-permanent income model of consumption: the treatment of seasonal fluctuations. The paper shows that when the seasonal fluctuations in consumption purchases are included in an analysis of the life cycle-permanent income model, there is no evidence in the aggregate data against the model. The estimates of the parameters of agents' utility functions obtained with seasonally unadjusted data are plausible, and the unadjusted data do not reject the overidentifying restrictions on the model.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261432
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261432
Y2  - 2024/03/22
